    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Tracking issue for https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/32142#issuecomment-3607107758\n\n\n\n> >  In practice, completion item lists are often large, and when multiple language servers are active, the overall time complexity becomes O(M × N). With two passes, it effectively becomes O(N²) in many real scenarios.\n> \n> \n> It's not O(N²), but currently the items are processed 4 times: Once to apply defaults, once to get the word boundary, once to filter and convert to complete-item, once to sort.\n> \n> Could probably optimize that a bit if profiling shows it is a problem. I'd think that for most servers the number of completion items is actually rather small. tailwind probably being an exception with it's thousands of css classes.\n> \n> \n> ---\n> \n> But one issue the current implementation does have is if a server were to provide several textEdits each with a different starting word boundary. `vim.fn.complete` needs the same starting point for all items. We could address that by normalizing (trimming or extending) the completion items relative to the left (or right?)-most starting point.\n> I hadn't seen any server which returns entries with mixed starting locations when I created lsp-compl (on which this code was based on). So I neglected that case.\n> \n> But note that to fix that, we'd have to keep iterating twice, because you need to figure out the left/right most position to be able to normalize the other entries. That requires 2 iterations.\n\n            ",
